Here's the completed code that uses OpenMP to compute the distance between the closest two points in parallel:

```cpp
#include <omp.h>
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>
#include <algorithm>

struct Point {
	double x, y;
};

// Function to calculate the Euclidean distance between two points
double distance(Point const& p1, Point const& p2) {
	return std::sqrt(std::pow(p2.x-p1.x, 2) + std::pow(p2.y-p1.y, 2));
}

// Function to find the closest pair of points in parallel using OpenMP
double closestPair(std::vector<Point> const& points) {
	// Initialize minimum distance to a large value
	double minDistance = std::numeric_limits<double>::max();

	#pragma omp parallel for reduction(min:minDistance)
	for (int i = 0; i < points.size(); ++i) {
		for (int j = i + 1; j < points.size(); ++j) {
			double dist = distance(points[i], points[j]);
			if (dist < minDistance) {
				minDistance = dist;
			}
		}
	}

	return minDistance;
}

// Example usage:
int main() {
	std::vector<Point> points = {{2, 3}, {12, 30}, {40, 50}, {5, 1}, {12, 10}, {3, 4}};
	double closestDist = closestPair(points);
	std::cout << "Closest distance: " << closestDist << std::endl;
	return 0;
}
```

This code uses OpenMP's `parallel for` directive to parallelize the nested loops that calculate the distances between all pairs of points. The `reduction(min:minDistance)` clause is used to ensure that the minimum distance is computed correctly in parallel.

Note: This implementation has a time complexity of O(n^2), where n is the number of points, because it checks every pair of points. For large datasets, you may want to consider using more efficient algorithms like the divide-and-conquer approach or k-d tree algorithm for nearest neighbor search.

